<subSubSection id="5EDA654AFFFBFFCFEA9F4B8DFA18FB83" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" type="description">
<paragraph id="167F36C1FFFBFFCFEA9F4B8DFEF2FC81" blockId="7.[192,598,717,780]" box="[192,379,753,780]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">
(
<figureCitation id="8EFB2A44FFFBFFCFEA984B8DFEC5FC86" box="[199,332,753,780]" captionStart="Figures 1–9" captionStartId="4.[192,279,831,857]" captionTargetBox="[243,1383,223,792]" captionTargetId="figure-449@4.[240,1392,213,801]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figures 1–9. Dorsal and ventral habitus of adult Chrysina specimens (1×). 1–2) C. clavellina Holotype male. 3–4) C. clavellina female. 5) C. lacordairei. 6) C. adelaida red morph. 7) C. adelaida green morph. 8) C. expansa. 9) C. adolphi." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4565329" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4565329/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Figures 6, 7</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="8EFB2A44FFFBFFCFEB084B8DFEFAFC81" box="[343,371,753,779]" captionStart="Figures 14–21" captionStartId="6.[192,279,1378,1404]" captionTargetBox="[212,1421,275,1280]" captionTargetId="figure-260@6.[192,1440,260,1316]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figures 14–21. Chrysina spp. genital structures. 14–19) Male genital capsule dorsal (d) and ventral (v), 8× original size. 14) C. clavellina (d). 15) C. clavellina (v). 16) C. arellanoi (d). 17) C. arellanoi (v). 18) C. lacordairei (d). 19) C. adelaida. 20–21) Female inferior genital plates. 20) C. clavellina. 21) C. arellanoi." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4565335" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4565335/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">19</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="167F36C1FFFBFFCFEB5F4A5FFA18FB83" blockId="7.[192,1442,803,1033]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">
This is a common and widespread species, found throughout most of 
<collectingCountry id="6ED77651FFFBFFCFEE4E4A5FFBEFFCB7" box="[1041,1126,803,829]" name="Mexico" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. We are aware of specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="D1C04D42FFFBFFCFEA814A39FED5FCD5" baseAuthorityName="Hope" baseAuthorityYear="1840" box="[222,348,837,863]" class="Insecta" family="Rutelidae" genus="Chrysina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="adelaida">
<emphasis id="24B4EAD3FFFBFFCFEA814A39FED5FCD5" box="[222,348,837,863]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">C. adelaida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from every state of 
<collectingCountry id="6ED77651FFFBFFCFE8604A39FD1BFCD5" box="[575,658,837,863]" name="Mexico" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Mexico</collectingCountry>
north of the Isthmus of Tehuantepec except 
<collectingRegion id="D404F823FFFBFFCFEED24A39FABEFCD5" box="[1165,1335,837,863]" country="Mexico" name="Baja California" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Baja California</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion id="D404F823FFFBFFCFEF2F4A39FEE9FC0B" country="Mexico" name="Baja California Sur" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Baja California Sur</collectingRegion>
. It has been found in pine-oak forests at elevations between 1300 and 3000 meters above sea level. Numerous specimens have been found in the Sierra Azul in Santa Inés del Monte at 
<quantity id="D1389B24FFFBFFCFEE2D4AF5FB41FC29" box="[1138,1224,905,931]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" unit="m" value="2300.0">2300 m</quantity>
, and in the vicinity of Santiago Clavellinas (2100–2300 and 
<quantity id="D1389B24FFFBFFCFE8234AD6FD59FC4F" box="[636,720,938,965]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.745" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" unit="m" value="2745.0">2745 m</quantity>
) in pine-oak forests (
<specimenCount id="00C6FD48FFFBFFCFE9E34AD6FB9BFC4E" box="[956,1042,938,965]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" type="male">5 males</specimenCount>
and 
<specimenCount id="00C6FD48FFFBFFCFEE184AD6FB38FC4F" box="[1095,1201,938,965]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" type="female">4 females</specimenCount>
) during August–September 2018 and 
<date id="627E1001FFFBFFCFEBD74AB0FE7DFC6C" box="[392,500,972,998]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" value="2019-07">July 2019</date>
. There are several common color morphs of 
<taxonomicName id="D1C04D42FFFBFFCFE9AA4AB1FBFDFC6C" baseAuthorityName="Hope" baseAuthorityYear="1840" box="[1013,1140,972,999]" class="Insecta" family="Rutelidae" genus="Chrysina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="adelaida">
<emphasis id="24B4EAD3FFFBFFCFE9AA4AB1FBFDFC6C" box="[1013,1140,972,999]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">C. adelaida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from reddish striped (
<figureCitation id="8EFB2A44FFFBFFCFEF2B4AB0FF58FB83" captionStart="Figures 1–9" captionStartId="4.[192,279,831,857]" captionTargetBox="[243,1383,223,792]" captionTargetId="figure-449@4.[240,1392,213,801]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figures 1–9. Dorsal and ventral habitus of adult Chrysina specimens (1×). 1–2) C. clavellina Holotype male. 3–4) C. clavellina female. 5) C. lacordairei. 6) C. adelaida red morph. 7) C. adelaida green morph. 8) C. expansa. 9) C. adolphi." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4565329" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4565329/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
) to mostly green (
<figureCitation id="8EFB2A44FFFBFFCFEBC44A92FE54FB83" box="[411,477,1006,1033]" captionStart="Figures 1–9" captionStartId="4.[192,279,831,857]" captionTargetBox="[243,1383,223,792]" captionTargetId="figure-449@4.[240,1392,213,801]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figures 1–9. Dorsal and ventral habitus of adult Chrysina specimens (1×). 1–2) C. clavellina Holotype male. 3–4) C. clavellina female. 5) C. lacordairei. 6) C. adelaida red morph. 7) C. adelaida green morph. 8) C. expansa. 9) C. adolphi." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4565329" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4565329/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). Adults of 
<taxonomicName id="D1C04D42FFFBFFCFE8034A92FD50FB82" baseAuthorityName="Hope" baseAuthorityYear="1840" box="[604,729,1006,1032]" class="Insecta" family="Rutelidae" genus="Chrysina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="adelaida">
<emphasis id="24B4EAD3FFFBFFCFE8034A92FD50FB82" box="[604,729,1006,1032]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">C. adelaida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are known to feed on the needles of pine trees (
<taxonomicName id="D1C04D42FFFBFFCFEEB24A93FAA2FB82" box="[1261,1323,1007,1032]" class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Pinus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="24B4EAD3FFFBFFCFEEB24A93FAA2FB82" box="[1261,1323,1007,1032]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Pinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
